{"actual_usd":0.156835,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":239,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No—always.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of my worn Bible and glance up at the clear morning sky a moment, letting the answer land plain before I dress it up.* \"Jesus did not become God’s Son at his baptism, and he did not become divine at any point. He was always the Son, and he was always divine.\"\n\n*I lean back a little, the bench giving a small creak under me.* \"His baptism was a revealing, not a promotion. That’s the Father saying, in public, who he already is: 'This is my beloved Son.' Same with the incarnation—he didn’t start being God when he was conceived in Mary’s womb. That’s when the eternal Son took on flesh.\"\n\n\"John opens there on purpose: 'In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God.'\" *I tap the Bible lightly with one finger.* \"And later: 'the Word became flesh.' Became flesh—yes. Became divine—no.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can also show you why some people read the baptism that way, and where that idea goes wrong.\"","rolling_24h_usd":29.538095000000016,"run_id":"0dfdb6b2-4f52-49b5-becb-d02c76cdcc05"}
